<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="186" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1081,2008]" pageId="3" pageNumber="186">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,286,1081,1107]" pageId="3" pageNumber="186">Etymology.</emphasis>
Dedicated to the Guane indigenous people, who inhabited the Zapatoca municipality and the municipalities of Los Santos, 
<collectingCountry box="[483,558,1117,1143]" name="Jordan" pageId="3" pageNumber="186">Jordán</collectingCountry>
and Cabrera, up to the junction of the Charalá or Fonce and Suárez or Saravita rivers, in the department of 
<collectingRegion box="[466,580,1153,1179]" country="Colombia" name="Santander" pageId="3" pageNumber="186">Santander</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[591,705,1153,1179]" name="Colombia" pageId="3" pageNumber="186">Colombia</collectingCountry>
. The Guane were particularly indigenous, as they had Caucasoid features, such as fair skin and taller than the average of the other Pre-columbian Indigenous.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
